{{Refimprove|date = February 2008}} '''Chewidden Thursday''' (also known as White Thursday, Chewidden Day or Jew-whidn) was a festival celebrated by the tin miners of West [[Cornwall]] on the last clear Thursday before (i.e. at least one week before) [[Christmas]]. The festival celebrated the discovery of 'white tin' or smelted tin by St Chiwidden, a little-known Cornish saint who in legend was an associate of [[St Piran]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Courtney|first1=Margaret Ann|title=Folklore & Legends of Cornwall|date=1973|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=0874710200|pages=6}}</ref>
[[Robert Hunt (scientist)|Robert Hunt]] in ''Popular Romances of the West of England'' states: *''The last Thursday – a clear week before Christmas Day – was formerly always claimed by the tinners as a holiday, and was called by them White-Thursday (Jew-whidn), because on this day, according to tradition, black tin (tin ore) was first melted and refined into white tin. From Jew-whidn to Chi-widden is an easy transition.''<ref>https://cornishculture.co.uk/portfolio/chewidden-thursday/</ref>
==See also== *[[Picrous Day]] *[[Tom Bawcock's Eve]] *[[St Piran's Day]]
